ground=http://home.earthlink.net/~nsmessageboard/ezboard/images/bar.jpg class=headings><font color=#FFFFFF>Comment</font></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uskyjim.showPublicProfile?language=EN>skyjim</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/globalBlack.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 22<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(9/22/02 11:56 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm3.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=99.topic&index=41>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Own a telescope?</span><hr size=1> The 10 inch will definitely show Neptune's disk, but you'll need some power and good seeing.  Uranus and Neptune look a lot like small planetary nebulae (which is where Herschel got the idea for the naming of planetaries - he noted that they resembled his discovery, Uranus, in the eyepiece) both in color and angular size.<br>
<br>
In the 18 (which is being rebuilt right now - I use my buddy's 20 inch a lot these days...) the Orion Nebula is an obvious pale lime green with hints of purple-pink under a dark, transparent sky.  Other large bright nebulae like the Lagoon have similar colors, but each is unique. Color discriimination is very tough at low light levels and you'll see interesting variations in the colors perceived by different persons on the same object through the same scope on a given night.  Personally I've always attributed that to the fact that we really <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> do</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> have personal variations in color perception, but also the fact that we are in effect working near the limits of detection for our  own visual system when we try to discriminate color in very dim objects.  The signal-to-noise ratio isn't very good.<br>
<br>
No matter how big a scope you get, there is always somebody with a bigger one.  For me, the 18 inch cured the aperture fever and it is also convenient to use since no ladder is needed - a stepstool is nice at zenith, but 80% of the time I can observe with my feet on the ground.   I'm very glad to have friends with 20, 25, and 28 inch scopes, though.  I just don't relish the hassle of setting up and using them.<br>
<br>
Clear Skies!<br>
<br>
Jim<br>
<br>
