<br>
I can imagine the hell it must be to setup those giant scopes. The 10 inch is probably all the scope I can handle, at least right now.  It seems to be a good mix of portability and performance.  Of course it's not exactly ultra-portable, but it only takes two trips out the door to set it up.  I usually put my planisphere, red flashlight, etc, in the base and carry it out separate from the telescope tube.   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uskyjim.showPublicProfile?language=EN>skyjim</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/globalBlack.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 23<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(9/24/02 1:43 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm3.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=99.topic&index=43>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Own a telescope?</span><hr size=1> The old saw about the best scope being the one you'll use is a fundamental truth!<br>
<br>
Once you get beyond around 10 inches or so, most people who travel to dark sky sites with dobs wind up eventually going for truss tube designs to keep the volume reasonable.  Once that happens, there is sort of a fixed overhead of about 10 - 15 minutes for setup and collimation.  My 18&quot; f4.5 takes the same amount of time to set up as my buddy's 20&quot; f5 does, but the eyepiece heights are the crucial diffference.  I whip all over the sky, while he tends to work a smaller area more methodically, driven in that direction by the inconvenience of having to reposition his stepladder when he slews.  Being sort of an Astronomical Steve Irwin type (You know, the crazy Aussie on Crocodile Hunter ), I bound around, all enthusiastic about sharing objects with people.  that makes the 18 and it's height suit me quite well.   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=hamster>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 154<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(9/25/02 4:48 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm3.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=99.topic&index=44>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/pubimage.asp?id_=638250 WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Own a telescope?</span><hr size=1> How do you prefer to clean the mirrors in your scopes?  With winter coming up I'm wondering if condensation might ruin the mirror with streaks and other dried water marks and I don't really want to get a rag and windex and wipe it down if you know what I mean.  Do you have problems with condensation and moisture forming on the mirror during winter?  Winter is one of my favorite times of years for stargazing so there's no way I'll be able to put it in the closet and wait till next summer to use it again.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uskyjim.showPublicProfile?language=EN>skyjim</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/globalBlack.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 24<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(9/25/02 11:56 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm3.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=99.topic&index=45>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Own a telescope?</span><hr size=1> The first way that I clean my mirrors is SELDOM!   You are better off with some dust and water spots than with sleeks in the coating from too much cleaning.  I'll look up a good mirror cleaning link and post it tomorrow.<br>
<br>
You'll proably have to have really horrendous dewing conditions to affect your primary mirror - with a full tube acting as a dewcap, it isn't all that susceptible to dewing.  The secondary is another story, and I've had times when mine started misting over - normally well after the guys with SCTs have dewed up corrector plates.  Often, you'll notice it on your eyepieces first, your breath and the moisture from your eye fogging the eyelens.  When this happens, stay calm and just wrap your hand around the eyepiece barrel - you'll be amazed at how quickly the fog diappears as some heat transfers into the eyepiece from your hand.  Obviously, you don't want to try this if it is forty below zero outside!<br>
<br>
I've installed a dew heater on my new secondary cage - had it built in when Protostar made the spider:<br>
<br>
