eft class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/fry1.gif" align=absmiddle>  Mirror cleaning</span><hr size=1> This guy cleans much as I do, although I've used immersion for the preliminary soak and reduced the time I actually run the water, on the theory that unfiltered tap water carries its own cargo of micro particles:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://members.aol.com/bemusabord/cleaning.html">members.aol.com/bemusabord/cleaning.html</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
Herre's another site which provides two alternatives:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.pcisys.net/~astrogirl/tips4.htm">www.pcisys.net/~astrogirl/tips4.htm</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
On those big eyepieces, at f5, your XT-10's focal ratio, you can't go past 35mm of focal length without exceeding 7mm of exit pupil diameter.  This doesn't mean that you shouldn't use the 2 inch eyepieces, but it does mean that your first should probably not be in the 50mm range.  For one thing, there are some superb wide field eyepieces in the 30 to 35mm range, and for another, the contrast will be better than a 50mm because of the greater magnification.  The exit pupil issue is about having a larger diameter image than can be made to enter your eye's pupil.  Very large exit pupils aren't so much &quot;wasting light&quot;, as dealing with contrast dropoff because the central obstruction becomes a factor in a newtonian.<br>
<br>
If you choose to work in this range, there are a number of nice choices.  I'm leaving out things like the 31mm Nagler, because of its weight (which creates balance issues) and expense (about the same price as youor scope).  That being said, I LOVE my 31mm Nagler......<br>
<br>
On the upper end of the market, you find things like the Televue 35mm Panoptic:  68 degree apparent field of view, field stop diameter 38.7 mm, and 24mm of eye relief .  In your scope, this will yield a true FOV of  1.76 degrees at 35X - three and a half full moons.   By contrast, the absolute best FOv you can get in a 1.25 barrel format is 1.23 degrees based on a field stop diameter of 27mm, which is about all that can be stuffed into the ID of a 1.25 eyepiece.  You have to have field stop diameters to accurately calculate true field of view - you can't just divide the claimed apparent field of view by the magnification if you want accurate numbers.  <br>
<br>
Another way cool 2&quot; eyepiece, although the focal length is really longer than optimum, is the 40mm Pentax XL.  I can't find a field stop diameter, but it is probably  just a tad smaller than the Panoptic based on this review:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.cloudynights.com/eyepieces/pentax40.htm">www.cloudynights.com/eyepieces/pentax40.htm</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
Both  f these are big ticket eyepieces, and budget may not allow this type of purchase for awhile.  Another excellent choice for reasonably priced eyepieces which perform well is University Optics.  The make a 2 inch 32mm eyepiece design called a Konig.  In the following comparison, you can tell that the guy loves his 32mm Konig!<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.cloudynights.com/eyepieces/Six%20Low%20Cost%202.html">www.cloudynights.com/eyepieces/Six%20Low%20Cost%202.html</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
These are bargains at $129.95 - less than half the cost of the 35mm Panoptic.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.universityoptics.com/uoep.htm#WIDE%202%22%20Oculars">www.universityoptics.com/uoep.htm#WIDE%202%22%20Oculars</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
Anyway, take your time, don't buy really cheap eyepieces - they are a waste of money.  The UO Konigs are the lowest cost 2&amp;quot; eyepieces I'd get for your XT-10.  If you can spring for the 35mm Panoptic, that would probably be my first choice, but they cost.  The good news is that you can pick them up on astromart occasionally and save some money.  I suspect people like me who have 31mm Naglers aren't using their 35mm Panoptics as much as they once did.<br>
<br>
Remember, your mileage may vary, and there are as many opinions on eyepieces as there are amateur astronomers.  The best bet is to go to a star party with lots of scopes and try to test drive eyepieces in your scope to see what works.  I loan people eyepieces for quick looks all the time while I'm observing, as long as I know where they have their scopes set up.......<br>
