f" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 26<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(10/2/02 9:16 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm3.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=99.topic&index=49>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Own a telescope?</span><hr size=1> Hey, Hamster, I think anybody who doesn't find themselves starting to think deeper thoughts while gazing at the wonders of the sky in a decent scope is either mentally dead or hopelessly self-absorbed.......<br>
<br>
The 32mm University is probably hard to beat in bang-for-the-buck quotient.  Two others you might consider are the Meade 32mm Superwide (still made) and the old TeleVue 32mm Wide Field (out of production but available used).   Both will give a nice wide field, albeit with a tad of field curvature - something which really bothers some people but not others.  I also think about the 40mm Pentax XL, even though the exit pupil is a bit big and the magnification a little lower than I prefer - it's cheaper than the 35mm Panoptic and lighter, even though I still think the Pan would be my first choice for a 2&quot; &quot;sweeper&quot; for your scope. <br>
<br>
You can get a 35mm Panoptic for about 300 used every once in a while on Astromart, and when I looked through one when they first came out, I immediately sold my 32mm Meade Superwide and got one.  There was a tiny bit more field, but the main difference was how much larger the area of well-corrected field was.  All of these give a tad bit of distortion at the extreme edge, but the 35 Pan definitely beat the older 32mms by TV and Meade which had been the de facto standard eyepieces in that niche for serious observers.<br>
<br>
I've never done a side-by-side between the University 32mm and the two from TV and Meade.  I'm sure the pricier eyepieces would show a little more field and perhaps better edge correction, but I doubt that it would be a hundred bucks worth of either.  The fact is that you hit diminishing returns pretty quickly - the best may cost twice what a decent eyepiece costs, but the view isn't necessarily perceived to be &quot;twice&quot; as good.  Beyond a certain point you become less tolerant of minor aberrations which might not even have been visible to you when you started out in the hobby.  My approach would be either to wait and save for the best possible eyepiece, or get one that is economical and serviceable to tide me over while I save for the optimum.  Other people don't think premium eyepieces are worth the hefty price tag.  It's a subjective question which only you can answer for yourself.<br>
<br>
If you ever make it down to my neck of the woods (Valencia, where Magic Mountain is)  or plan to try a star party at Mt. Pinos, I'd be happy to loan you some eyepieces for test drives.  It's the best way to see what works for you.<br>
<br>
Clear Skies!<br>
<br>
Jim<br>
<br>
